results.reasoning: Pineal region midline enhancing mass causing aqueductal obstruction and hydrocephalus in an adult with biopsy and excellent radiotherapy response — classic for a radiosensitive germinoma (intracranial germ cell tumour). Imaging and treatment response make dermoid, tectal glioma, pineoblastoma and meningioma less likely.

MRI shows a lobulated solid mass along the flexor tendon sheath at the volar wrist with heterogeneous low T2 signal and enhancement consistent with hemosiderin-laden tenosynovial giant-cell tumor; not purely cystic so not a ganglion; fibroma would be smaller and more homogeneous.

Imaging shows a well-defined multilocular cystic mass in the left upper quadrant with thin septations, peripheral enhancement and adjacent inflammatory change; clinical fever and leukocytosis indicate superimposed infection. Findings favor a mesenteric lymphatic malformation (lymphangioma) with inflammatory changes. Duplication cysts are usually bowel-attached and pediatric; mesothelial cysts are typically pelvic and unilocular; non-pancreatic pseudocyst less likely without pancreatitis/trauma history.

13-year-old with adnexal mass and elevated androstenedione (virilization), MRI mixed solid-cystic ovarian mass and histology showing retiform/poorly differentiated pattern consistent with Sertoli-Leydig cell tumor (sex cord-stromal tumor).

Well-defined small submucosal intraluminal polypoid rectal lesion with marked diffusion restriction and intense homogeneous contrast enhancement, typical for a small rectal neuroendocrine tumour (carcinoid). Findings are not typical for mucosal-based adenocarcinoma, exophytic heterogeneous GIST, haemangioma (would show very high T2 and phleboliths), or MALT lymphoma (more diffuse wall involvement).

Multiple bilateral, well-defined round subcutaneous low-attenuation nodules with fat-like density in the buttocks/thighs consistent with injected oil/paraffin droplets (lipogranulomas). Appear as fat-density globules, not soft-tissue metastases, neurofibromas or air.

Well-marginated fusiform soft-tissue mass along the course of the posterior tibial nerve with T2-hyperintense signal, internal vascularity on US and clinical nerve compression — appearance most consistent with a neurogenic tumour (e.g., schwannoma). Other options less likely given location, morphology and patient age.

Fever and left flank pain in a patient with horseshoe kidney. Imaging shows a complex multiloculated cystic lesion with central nonenhancing necrosis/debris and peripheral/septal enhancement on CT and complex echoes on US—features most consistent with a renal abscess rather than a solid neoplasm.

Pineal midline mass causing obstructive hydrocephalus in an adult male with biopsy-proven lesion and dramatic response to radical radiotherapy. Imaging shows a well-enhancing pineal lesion (possible central calcification) and the clinical course is classic for a radiosensitive germ cell tumour/germinoma rather than pineoblastoma or dermoid; tectal glioma and meningioma are less likely. Therefore intracranial germ cell tumour (germinoma) is most likely.

Well-defined cystic multiloculated lesion at the volar wrist with high T2 signal and rim/septal enhancement consistent with a ganglion cyst. Imaging lacks low T2/hemosiderin or solid fibrous characteristics of GCTTS or fibroma of tendon sheath.

CT shows a well-defined thin-walled multiloculated cystic mesenteric lesion with thin enhancing septa and adjacent inflammatory changes; clinical fever and leukocytosis fit infected/inflamed lymphangioma. Duplication cysts usually show a gut-wall signature and a close bowel wall relationship; pseudocyst would require pancreatitis history. Most consistent diagnosis: lymphangioma with inflammatory changes.

Adolescent with virilizing androgen elevation (↑ delta‑4‑androstenedione) and a large heterogeneous solid–cystic right adnexal mass on MRI; histology images demonstrate retiform/poorly differentiated Sertoli‑Leydig morphology. Findings are classic for Sertoli‑Leydig cell tumour.

Well-defined small submucosal rectal nodule with homogeneous marked arterial-phase enhancement and diffusion restriction on MRI—typical appearance of a rectal neuroendocrine tumour (carcinoid). Findings are unlike diffuse homogeneous concentric thickening of lymphoma, the large heterogeneous pattern of GIST, the very T2-bright haemangioma, or infiltrative adenocarcinoma.

CT shows numerous bilateral, well-defined subcutaneous rounded nodules with fat-like attenuation in buttocks and thighs, most consistent with self-injected oil/silicone droplets (oil bubbles). Appearance matches described ‘oil/silicone’ injection cases and differs from soft-tissue-density metastases, neurofibromas, or air.

Imaging shows a well-defined fusiform, encapsulated, enhancing soft-tissue mass along the course of the posterior tibial nerve in the tarsal tunnel with target/fascicular appearance and neurovascular displacement causing tibial nerve compression. Features are classic for a benign neurogenic tumour (schwannoma/neurofibroma). Other options (Ewing sarcoma, synovial sarcoma, UPS, lymphoma) are less likely given location, morphology, and patient age.

CT demonstrates peripheral nodular/persistent enhancement with a possible feeding vessel and centripetal fill-in appearance consistent with a vascular lesion. Imaging pattern matches renal haemangioma (peripheral nodular enhancement that persists into the portal phase) rather than abscess (which shows irregular rim enhancement and inflammatory changes) or RCC/oncocytoma. Therefore renal haemangioma is most likely.
